What are Trigger Rules?

Trigger Rules define conditions required for a task to execute.

They control downstream behavior.


---

Default Trigger Rule

all_success

Default behavior.

Meaning:

All upstream tasks must succeed


---

Example

task1 → success
task2 → success
       ↓
task3 runs


---

Problem with Branching

Example:

branch_a → success
branch_b → skipped

Downstream task may not execute because:

not all upstream tasks succeeded


---

Trigger Rule Flow

Upstream Tasks
      ↓
Trigger Rule Evaluated
      ↓
Should Task Run?


---

Setting Trigger Rule

Example:

trigger_rule="one_success"


---

Common Trigger Rules

Trigger Rule	Meaning

all_success	all upstream success
one_success	at least one success
none_failed	no failures
all_failed	all upstream failed
all_done	execute regardless of status



---

one_success

Meaning

Task runs if:

At least one upstream task succeeds


---

Example

task1 → success
task2 → failed
       ↓
downstream runs


---

none_failed

Meaning

Task runs if:

No upstream task failed

Skipped tasks allowed.


---

Example

task1 → success
task2 → skipped
       ↓
downstream runs

Very important after branching.


---

all_done

Meaning

Task runs regardless of:

success

failure

skipped



---

Used For

Commonly used in:

cleanup tasks

notifications

final reporting



---

Example

trigger_rule="all_done"


---

Real Branching Example

Branch
          /      \
      success   skipped
          \      /
        Final Task

Without proper trigger rule:

Final task may never execute


---

Full Example DAG

from airflow import DAG
from airflow.operators.python import PythonOperator
from airflow.operators.empty import EmptyOperator
from datetime import datetime

def success():
    print("Success")

with DAG(
    dag_id="trigger_rule_example",
    start_date=datetime(2025, 1, 1),
    schedule="@daily",
    catchup=False
) as dag:

    task1 = PythonOperator(
        task_id="task1",
        python_callable=success
    )

    task2 = EmptyOperator(
        task_id="task2"
    )

    final_task = EmptyOperator(
        task_id="final_task",
        trigger_rule="none_failed"
    )

    [task1, task2] >> final_task


